s." The obligations that fieldwork engenders among researchers and local communities are exemplified by contributors who are often socially engaged with the peoples and places they work. In its focus on Asia and the Pacific Islands, the collection offers ethnographic updates on topics that range from ritual money burning in China to the militarization of Hawai'i to the social role of text messages in identifying marriage partners in Vanuatu to the cultural power of robots in Japan. Thought provoking, sometimes humorous, these cultural encounters will resonate with readers and provide valuable talking points for exploring the human diversity that makes the study of ourselves and each other simultaneously rewarding and challenging.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEthnologyxFieldworkzAsia. 0aEthnologyxFieldworkzOceania. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aAikau, Hokulani K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAshton, Geoff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Mary Tuti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBettinger, Keith Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlake, C. Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBodemer, Margaret Barnhill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasumbal-Salazar, Melisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosta, LeeRay M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCottino, Gaia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz, Lynette Hi‘ilani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinney, Suzanne S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re